ving bowl and garnish with chopped fresh parsley.\n3. Serve with pita bread, vegetables, or crackers. \n\n## 3.  Kibbeh (Lebanese Meatballs)\n\nThese hearty meatballs are a staple in Lebanese cuisine.  They are made with bulgur wheat, ground beef, and spices, and can be served as an appetizer, main dish, or part of a larger platter. \n\n**Yields:** 4-6 servings\n\n**Nutritional Information per serving (approximate):**\n\n* Calories: 350 kcal\n* Protein: 20g\n* Carbohydrates: 35g\n* Fat: 15g\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n* 1 cup (240 ml) bulgur wheat, cooked according to package directions\n* 500g ground beef\n* 1 large onion, finely chopped\n* 2 cloves garlic, minced\n* 1/2 cup (120 ml) chopped fresh parsley\n* 1 tsp (5g) ground cumin\n* 1/2 tsp (2.5g) ground coriander\n* 1/4 tsp salt\n* 1/4 tsp black pepper\n* 1/4 cup (60ml) olive oil\n* 1/4 cup (60ml) water \n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1. In a large bowl, combine the cooked bulgur wheat, ground beef, onion, garlic, parsley, cumin, coriander, salt, and pepper. Mix well with your hands. \n2. Shape the mixture into small meatballs, about 2 cm in diameter.  You can also form the mixture into patties for a kibbeh burger. \n3. Heat the olive oil in a large skillet or pot over medium heat.  \n4. Cook the meatballs for 5-7 minutes, or until cooked through and browned, turning them occasionally. \n5.  Add the water to the skillet and cook for 5 minutes more, or until the sauce has slightly thickened. \n6.  Serve hot, with a side of rice, vegetables, or a yogurt sauce. \n\n**Tips:**\n\n*  For a more decadent kibbeh, add a handful of pine nuts to the mixture. \n* You can serve the kibbeh with a sprinkle of toasted pine nuts, a dollop of yogurt, or a drizzle of lemon juice for extra flavor. \n* Feel free to adjust the spices to your preference.\n\nEnjoy exploring these delicious Lebanese recipes!"
