                    text(
                        "Here are the details for those Chard recipes, all dairy-free and egg-free: \n\n## Chard Salad with Toasted Almonds and Feta (Dairy-Free)\n\nThis salad is a vibrant and delicious combination of flavors and textures.  The sweet and savory notes of the roasted chard are balanced by the crunch of the toasted almonds and the tanginess of the feta cheese (dairy-free).\n\n**Yields:** 4 servings\n\n**Nutritional Information per serving (approximate):**\n\n* Calories: 250 kcal\n* Protein: 8g\n* Carbohydrates: 30g\n* Fat: 10g\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n* 1 bunch Swiss chard, stems removed and chopped, leaves roughly chopped\n* 1 tbsp olive oil\n* 1/4 cup (30g) walnuts, toasted\n* 1/4 cup (40g) crumbled dairy-free feta cheese (or vegan feta alternative)\n* 1/4 cup (40g) dried cranberries\n* 1/4 cup (60 ml)  lemon juice\n* 1/4 cup (60 ml) olive oil\n* 1 tbsp (15 ml) Dijon mustard\n* 1/4 tsp salt\n* 1/4 tsp black pepper\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1. **Blanch the Chard:**  Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the chard and cook for 1-2 minutes, or until wilted. Drain the chard and immediately plunge it into an ice bath to stop the cooking process.  \n2. **Toast the Walnuts:** In a dry skillet over medium heat, toast the walnuts for 3-4 minutes, or until fragrant. \n3. **Make the Dressing:** In a jar or bowl, whisk together the lemon juice, olive oil, Dijon mustard, salt, and pepper. \n4. **Assemble the Salad:**  In a large bowl, combine the blanched chard, toasted walnuts, crumbled feta cheese, and dried cranberries. \n5. Pour the dressing over the salad and toss gently to coat evenly. Serve immediately. \n\n**Tips:**\n\n*  You can use other nuts, such as almonds or pecans, instead of walnuts. \n*  To add a sweet and spicy touch, add a few chopped dates or a pinch of red pepper flakes to the salad. \n* Serve with toasted whole grain bread or crusty bread for a heartier meal.\n\nEnjoy this flavorful and nutritious salad!\n\n\n## Chard and Potato Gratin (Dairy-Free and Egg-Free)\n\nThis dish is a comforting and creamy take on a classic French gratin.  The combination of chard and potatoes creates a wholesome and flavorful dish that's both dairy-free and egg-free.\n\n**Yields:** 4 servings\n\n**Nutritional Information per serving (approximate):**\n\n* Calories: 300 kcal\n* Protein: 5g\n* Carbohydrates: 50g\n* Fat: 10g\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n* 1 bunch Swiss chard, stems removed and chopped, leaves roughly chopped \n* 2 large potatoes, thinly sliced \n* 1/4 cup (60 ml) olive oil \n* 2 cloves garlic, minced\n* 1/2 tsp dried thyme \n* 1/4 tsp salt\n* 1/4 tsp black pepper\n* 1/2 cup (120 ml)  unsweetened almond milk or unsweetened cashew milk\n* 1 tbsp nutritional yeast\n* 1 tbsp (15g) all-purpose flour\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1. Preheat oven to 180°C (350°F). Lightly grease a 9x13 inch baking dish.\n2. Blanch the Chard:  Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the chard and cook for 1-2 minutes, or until wilted. Drain the chard and immediately plunge it into an ice bath to stop the cooking process.  \n3. **Layer the Vegetables:**  In the prepared baking dish, layer half of the potatoes. Sprinkle with a little salt and pepper, and a sprinkle of the minced garlic. Top with half of the blanched chard. Repeat the layers with the remaining potatoes and chard, ending with chard.\n4. **Make the Sauce:** In a saucepan, whisk together the almond milk (or cashew milk), nutritional yeast, and flour until smooth. Heat over medium heat, stirring constantly, until the sauce thickens slightly, about 2-3 minutes. \n5. Pour the sauce over the layered vegetables in the baking dish. \n6. Bake for 30-35 minutes, or until the potatoes are tender and the sauce is bubbly and golden brown. \n7. Let cool for 5 minutes before serving. \n\n**Tips:**\n\n* For a more intense flavor, add a pinch of nutmeg or a small pinch of cayenne pepper to the sauce.\n*  You can use a different type of milk, such as coconut milk or oat milk, in place of almond or cashew milk.\n\nEnjoy this hearty and flavorful gratin! \n\n## Chard and Chickpea Curry (Dairy-Free)\n\nThis recipe combines the earthy flavors of chard and chickpeas with the warming spices of an Indian curry.\n\n**Yields:** 4 servings\n\n**Nutritional Information per serving (approximate):**\n\n* Calories: 400 kcal\n* Protein: 15g\n* Carbohydrates: 55g\n* Fat: 10g\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n* 1 tbsp (15 ml) olive oil\n* 1 large onion, chopped\n* 2 cloves garlic, minced\n* 1 inch ginger, peeled and minced\n* 1 tbsp (15g) curry powder \n* 1 tsp (5g) ground cumin\n* 1/2 tsp (2.5g) turmeric\n* 1 (400g) can diced tomatoes, undrained\n* 400 ml coconut milk\n* 200 ml vegetable broth\n* 1 (400g) can chickpeas, rinsed and drained\n* 1 bunch Swiss chard, stems removed and chopped, leaves roughly chopped\n* 1/4 cup (60 ml) chopped fresh cilantro\n* Salt and pepper to taste\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1. Heat olive oil in a large pot over medium heat. Add onion, garlic, and ginger and cook until softened, about 5 minutes.\n2. Stir in curry powder, cumin, and turmeric. Cook for 1 minute, stirring constantly, to release the aromas. \n3. Add diced tomatoes, coconut milk, and vegetable broth. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low, cover, and simmer for 10 minutes.\n4.  Add chickpeas to the pot. Cover and simmer for 15-20 minutes, or until chickpeas are heated through.\n5.  Add the chard to the pot.  Simmer for 5 minutes more, or until wilted.\n6. Stir in cilantro and season with salt and pepper to taste.\n\n**Tips:**\n\n* To add a touch of heat, add a pinch of cayenne pepper or chili flakes to the curry. \n*  Serve with brown rice or quinoa for a complete meal.\n*  Garnish with chopped cashews or a sprinkle of chopped cilantro for extra flavor and texture.\n\nEnjoy this flavorful and satisfying curry!\n\n\n## Chard and Mushroom Stir-Fry (Dairy-Free and Egg-Free)\n\nThis stir-fry is a quick and easy vegetarian dish that’s packed with flavor and nutrients. It combines the earthy flavors of chard and mushrooms with a simple yet savory sauce.\n\n**Yields:** 2 servings\n\n**Nutritional Information per serving (approximate):**\n\n* Calories: 300 kcal\n* Protein: 10g\n* Carbohydrates: 35g\n* Fat: 10g\n\n**Ingredients:**\n\n* 1 tbsp (15ml) olive oil\n* 1 bunch Swiss chard, stems removed and chopped, leaves roughly chopped \n* 200g cremini or button mushrooms, sliced\n* 2 cloves garlic, minced\n* 1/4 cup (60ml) soy sauce \n* 1 tbsp (15ml) rice vinegar\n* 1 tsp (5ml) sesame oil\n* 1/2 tsp (2.5g)  ginger, grated \n* 1/4 tsp salt\n* 1/4 tsp black pepper\n\n**Instructions:**\n\n1. Heat olive oil in a large skillet or wok over medium-high heat.  Add the chard and cook for 3-4 minutes, or until slightly wilted. \n2. Remove the chard from the skillet and set aside. \n3.  Add the mushrooms to the skillet and cook until softened and slightly browned, about 5 minutes. \n4. Stir in garlic and cook for 30 seconds, or until fragrant.\n5.  Add the chard back to the skillet and toss to combine.\n6. In a small bowl, whisk together the soy sauce, rice vinegar, sesame oil, and ginger until smooth.  \n7. Pour the sauce over the chard and mushroom mixture. Toss gently to coat. \n8. Cook for 1-2 minutes, or until heated through.\n9. Serve immediately over cooked rice or noodles.  Garnish with chopped green onions or a sprinkle of sesame seeds, if desired. \n\n**Tips:**\n\n* Feel free to use other types of mushrooms, such as shiitake or oyster mushrooms, or add a mix of different mushrooms.\n*  You can adjust the sauce by adding a touch of honey, maple syrup, or a pinch of red pepper flakes for a spicy kick. \n*  This dish pairs well with a side of steamed rice, quinoa, or noodles.\n\nEnjoy this healthy and satisfying stir-fry!"
                    )
